> Chinese eggplant is longer and thinner-skinned than its Italian cousin, making it perfect for stir-frying. Sautéed with yellow squash, pork, and an umami-packed sauce, this stir-fry hits all the marks. Brown rice is a healthy swap we prefer for its heartiness.

Cook the @brown rice{3/4%cup}: Bring a #medium pot{} of salted water to boil with the
rice and @chicken stock concentrate{1}. Cook for ~{25-30%minutes}, or until tender.
Drain, like pasta, then return to the pot. Cover to steam.

Wash and dry all produce. Cut the @Chinese eggplant{1} into ½-inch cubes. Thinly
slice the @yellow squash{1} into rounds. Trim, then thinly slice the @scallions{2}
on a diagonal, keeping the greens and whites separate. Thinly slice the
@garlic{2%cloves}. Cut the @lime{1} into wedges.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium heat.
Add the eggplant and squash and cook, tossing for ~{7-8%minutes}, or until tender
and golden brown. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Remove from the
pan and set aside.

Heat a drizzle of oil in the same pan over medium heat. Add the scallion whites
and garlic and cook, tossing for ~{1-2%minutes}, until slightly softened. Add the
@ground pork{8%ounce} to the pan and cook, breaking up the meat into pieces, for
~{3-4%minutes}, until browned and cooked through. Season with salt and pepper.

Return the squash and eggplant to the pan. Add the @soy sauce jar{1} and cook,
tossing until the vegetables have been warmed through.

Serve: Plate the pork and Chinese eggplant stir-fry on a bed of brown rice and
squeeze over with a wedge of lime juice. Garnish with the scallion greens and
enjoy!